
The Danish States Railway, or D.S.B. Line (Danske Stats Baner)

A Potted History and Facts about the Line:

Length: 344.32 Miles

The line is build up from different railway lines with different
names, but I call it here 'The DSB Lyntog' line after the fastest
train there is in Denmark, (Lyntog = Lightning Train) which serves
this the longest stretch of line in the country.

The DSB Lyntog Line runs from Frederikshavn (Havn = Harbour) situated
in the northern part of the Jutland peninsula (see map) to København
(Copenhagen) the Capital of Denmark. On the way the line crosses one
fjord and two 'belts'.

The first railway line to open in Denmark was the stretch between
Roskilde and Copenhagen which came into service in 1847 and is still
in use today, upgraded from one 14 mph track, to the 4 fast lines it
has today.

From 1871 it was possible to take a train journey all the way from
Frederikshavn to Copenhagen, the line then was 332.5 miles long but
required the use of 3 ferry crossings:

1: The narrow stretch of the Limfjord between the northern part of
Jutland which is actually a large island and the rest of Jutland.
The town on the northern bank of the fjord is Nørre-Sundby, on the
south bank lies Aalborg.

2: The Little Belt (Lillebælt) which lies between the peninsula of
Jutland and the island of Funen (Fyn).

3: The Great Belt (Storebælt) which divides Funen and the island of
Zealand, where the capital Copenhagen is situated.

This divided the original railway journey into 4 parts:

Part 1: Frederikshavn - Nørre-Sundby (Opened 1871). Ferry to Aalborg.
Eight years later in 1879 the first railway bridge over the Limfjord
opened, and the 1st and 2nd part was connected.

Part 2: Aalborg to Fredericia (Opened in 1869). Ferry to the island
of Funen, to Strib harbour, and to join the train again at
Middelfart. The ferry opened in 1866. From 1935 when the Little
Belt Bridge (Lillebæltsbro) was opened, joining Jutland and Funen the
2nd and 3rd parts were connected too.

Part 3: Middelfart to Nyborg (Opened 1865).  Ferry to Zealand. From
1935 it was possible to take the train, with no changing, all the way
from Frederikshavn to Nyborg ferry harbour, in all 263.46 miles.

In Nyborg (which actually means Newcastle!) travellers had to change
from train to ferry by foot, a walk of 1/2 a mile. 1883 saw the
introduction of the purpose built railway ferries but it was only the
post and goods wagons that could go on board. In 1886 however a new
ferry harbour platform was built next to the ferries so the passengers
now only had a few minutes walk. It was not until 1904 that passengers
could actually enjoy the comfort of having the sleeping cars (Wagon-
lit) taken across the belt.

Crossing the 15.2 mile wide belt was often difficult and uncomfortable
due to the weather and current conditions, and as early as 1886 the
first plans were drawn up to dig a tunnel for the railway under the
sea. It was planned to use horse drawn railway wagons as the smoke
from the steam engines was considered to be too much of a problem. But
this never came to anything.

After World War two express trains had 4 wagons ferried 
over the belt twice a day in both directions. The oldest Lyntog was taken 
over twice daily from 1935 (except during WW2 when this service was 
suspended), as was the 'new' MA-Lyntog which started in 1962.  From 1968 
there have been modern InterCity ferries with capacity enough to take all 
the 8 wagons over at once, one an hour in each direction, from early 
morning until late night. So crossing the belt still means 1 hour of 
sailing today.

However from late autumn this year, 1996 the post and freight trains
will use the new Great Belt bridge and tunnel and from the summer
timetable 1997 all trains will use the bridge and tunnel.

Approximately in the middle of the Great Belt lies the small island of
Sprogø, dividing the belt into a western and eastern part. From the
island of Funen to Sprogø, the western part, there is a so called 'low
bridge' used by both trains and cars. It's 4.1 miles long, this is
called 'Storebælt Vest'. Once on the island cars continue over a high
bridge to Zealand, the eastern part. Trains however use a 5.7 mile
long tunnel, known as 'Storebælt Øst'. By this, for the first time
since the last ice age, all the major areas of Denmark are connected.

Part 4: Korsør to Copenhagen (opened 1847) - With the first railway
line from Roskilde to Copenhagen.

But you can now already have the experience of driving the full line
now, as it will be from 1997!



The D.S.B. Lyntog line


Here is some information about the line. It's in two parts, general
information followed by what you can see en route.

Alphabet: I'm using the Danish alphabet and spellings in all the names
of stations and places, just as if you were travelling here in Denmark
(For this to show up correctly on screen you'll have to install the
revised version of the TD font, please see the notes at the end.)

Buildings: I have spend a lot of time creating some buildings, I have
concentrated on the larger towns, station buildings and a few
'landmark' buildings, however a little imagination would make a nice
travelling companion here!

Engines: There are 5 types specifically made for the D.S.B. line:

Lyntog: MA trains. This is the one I wish to use on the Lyntog's line.
It's know in Europe as a TEE train, in Germany a Class VT 11. In
Denmark there is now one in the national railway museum in Odense, on
the island of Funen. The rest of the fleet was sold to Poland for a
symbolic sum of about 10 pence. They were in their heyday the fastest
and most luxurious trains here, they were named after the various
parts of the country that they connected to the capital. Not only did
they run on my DSB Line but they also served the north-west and
southern areas of Jutland. I have included the four serving Aalborg
and Frederikshavn. They have a bulbous nose and an elevated cab. (See
article in Today's Railways issue 13 1996) One train contained 8
carriages, the carriages at each end being power cars (1100 hp each)
but there was also space for passengers. They were specially made to
fit onto the ferries over the Great Belt, the tracks onboard could
take 2 x 4 carriages, that is half the train. Therefore they had a
second drivers seat in two wagons situated in the middle of the train
to allow for easier manoeuvrability when driving onboard, these were
elevated to allow people to walk through, when they were connected.
They ran until 1990.

MF-IC3: Diesel, the new Danish train fleet, no power engines but
elevated by bus motors underneath. Each set consists of three
carriages with a total of 1600 h.p. Acceleration is good due to it's
lightweight construction. Top speed is 125mph. Accelerating from 0-
75mph (120Km/h) in under 2 minutes. They can form a train of up to 5
sets (15 carriages) but my data is based on 3 sets (9 carriages) Due
to their exceptional acceleration capabilities they are able to stop
at more stations on the Frederikshavn-Copenhagen route than the old MA
Lyntog did, in a much shorter time. Since the withdrawal of the MA-
Lyntog in 1990 there were no longer any Lyntog connections to and from
Copenhagen, however in the last couple of years certain MF-IC3
departures have been upgraded to 'Lyntog' status but only from Aalborg
to Copenhagen. You'll find and example of this in my DSBline for TD2.
(There is also an electric variant, IR4 which will be used as a
regional train).

EA: Modern electric engines 25000 Volt effect 4.0 MW (aprox. 5435h.p.)

MY: Dieselelectric, the oldest Danish diesel 1950 h.p. Some still at
work, mostly taken over by the stronger MZ.

MZ: Dieselelectric, the most powerful DSB ever had at 3900 h.p.


