Line: I've tired to make the line as accurate as possible, however
there will always be some minor differences.

Line power: The line is now electrified from Fredericia to Copenhagen,
the rest being doing in phases but you can choose from both diesel and
electric, within TD2

Radio system: In Denmark we use the Storno system of radios, when you
drive on the line you'll have information boards with the channels
used 'from here on forward' - you'll experience them here in the name
display to the right on the screen. They all look like this:
FC ÅR A65 D/C35   and here is the code:

FC: Fjernstyrings Central (Central Remote Main signal box) ÅR: In
Denmark all station names have a letter code as well, in this case
Århus. A65: Radio main channel A for the line, were all trains can be
connected through the FC but also if one driver sees any danger or if
an emergency situation arises he can by one touch of a button warn
directly all the trains within the A number section he's on, so can of
course the FC. D/C 35: The 'local' signal box or station radio channel
can only receive messages if an emergency A arises.

Signals: In TD2 only the English system of signals are shown, but even
when they are rather different from the Danish system, the 'effect' in
the drive is nearly the same.

Stations: There are 5 different type of stations represented:

1: Central Main Stations, only three, one is Copenhagen (København),
the second at Århus, and the third in Fredericia. (Special long
platforms ending up in a large station building, and selectable for
stops)

2: Main stations with a long platform and with or without a platform
roof (selectable for stops)

3: Local or country stations, shown here as a white/grey platform and
station building situated at the side of the line where the actually
station is. Always with a red roof.

4: Abandoned platforms in grey, often still with the buildings, always
with a dark grey roof - look abandoned!

5: Halt, a stop with only a primitive platform. Here they are shown
dark grey without any buildings. There used to be a lot of them up
until the 1930's, I have only shown a few, but the names of them all
come up just to indicate where your are on the line. You will also see
a few times the word Skov meaning forest and Sø meaning lake coming
up.


The train is always seen on the left hand side track when passing the
local or abandoned stations (no stop)

Timings: The timings are my estimations as a timetable has not been
produced to cover the use of the Great Belt link, but correct timing
files will be available as soon as they are published.

Tracks: It's right hand driving in Denmark, as well as in the rest of
Scandinavia and Germany, trains however only run on the left in TD2.

Future plans: More new Danish lines and the Lyntog's line as a vintage
line with steam and semaphore signals.

