Route description and Landmarks, listed in miles.

The line between Frederikshavn and Aalborg is single track with three
passing places where the southbound trains must wait for trains coming
in the opposite direction. These passing places are station loops. You
will therefore notice that the times within TD2 on this part of the
line are very slack in order to cope with this but this situation
can't be reproduced in TD2 (yet!)

0.018 From Frederikshavn Harbour the train connects with the ferries
from Oslo in Norway and Götenburg in Sweden. (I'm planing to make the
line of the North Arrow train which goes from here all the way down to
Hamburg Altona)

1.018 Frederikshavn town station, from here there is a private line
running up to the northern tip of Jutland to Skagen town and ferries
to Norway. The line is single track from Frederikshavn to Aalborg.

23.80 Hjørring, private line to Hirtshals and ferry to Norway. Note
the FC control box.

37.50 Store Vildmose. The next 5 miles is through the largest moor in
Denmark

51.78 Limfjord bridge, note the middle part can open for ships.

53.63 Aalborg the fourth largest town in Denmark,(160,000 inhabitants)
from here double track all the way to Copenhagen. Note the old water
tower 53, the big FC control box, 53.80.

70.20 Rold Skov. The next five miles runs through the largest forest
in Denmark, approximately in the middle there is a lake and what use
to be a very popular stop (Mosskov) for people for 'a day out' by
train up until the 1960s.

104.06 Randers, note the old signaling box at 103.40 and the new FC
control box at 104.

104.50 Gudenå the largest river in Denmark is crossed by the train
107.10 three times. This part of the line was very difficult due to
113.00 the river. The station at 112.36 Langå actually means long 
river

140.21 Århus, the second largest town in Denmark, (250,000
inhabitants) special long platform, continue into the great railway
hall, and stop at the board/signal there. Branch line to Århus harbour
and Grenå. Private line to Odder.

153.96 Skanderborg, No stop for the Lyntog trains Line, connection to
the middle, west and north-western parts of Jutland

187.75 Vejle Fjord Bridge. You will pass under this motorway bridge
twice, before and after Vejle station, the first time as you travel on
the fjords northerly bank going from east to west to Vejle town and
then, after the station, travelling west to east along the fjords
southern bank. (See map)

192.26 Vejle, No stop for the old Lyntog trains, line connection to
west and north-western parts of Jutland. The new IC3 Lyntog stops here
instead of Fredericia

193.47 Vejle Fjord Bridge.

187.70 Fredericia, special long platform, continue into the railway
hall, and stop at the board/signal there. Connections to the west,
Esbjerg line (Ferries to Harwich) Northwest cost and the southern
part of Jutland and down to Germany

210.75 Little Belt bridge (Lillebæltbroen), the connection between
Jutland and Funen opened in 1935.

213.96 Middelfart, No stop for the Lyntog trains.

245.66 Odense, the third largest town in Denmark,(200,000 inhabitants)
birth place for the famous story teller Hans Christian Andersen. A
line to Svendborg (south)

263.46 Nyborg, No stop for the Lyntog trains. Until 1997 the ferry
harbour at Great Belt, now the start of the new bridge and tunnel.

263.99 The Great Belt (Storebælt) west bridge (see above)

268.10 The small island Sprogø (see above)

269.10 The Great Belt east tunnel (see above)

271.00 EL UD (Electricity Off) This is the start of a neutral section
that is 0.65 miles long. This was inserted as the current used on
Zealand is incompatible with the rest of the country. The steep
gradients within the tunnel are then used so that the engine can
free-wheel from one electricity section to the other.

271.62 EL IND (Electricity On) Ready for the steep climb out of the
tunnel up to Zealand.

276.36 Korsør, No stop for the Lyntog trains. Until 1997 the ferry
harbour for the Great Belt, now the end of the new great belt tunnel
and bridge.

287.46 Slagelse, No stop for the Lyntog trains, private line
connection to Holbæk

305.56 Ringsted, No stop for the Lyntog trains Line connection to
south of Zealand and the islands of Falster & Møn (Ferries to Germany)

324.70 Building: Roskilde Cathedral, the enormous building where all
the Danish Kings and Queens are buried from 1413 to the present day,
however the oldest tombs date back to 1250.

325.36 Roskilde, connection to south east and south of Zealand

330.90 Høje Taastrup, No stop for the old Lyntog trains. A new modern
satellite railway station for Copenhagen, opened just before the old
Lyntog was withdrawn. The new IC3 Lyntog stops here instead of
Roskilde.

330.90 Copenhagen Central station, capital of Denmark, the largest
town. Train line up to Helsingor (Sweden by rail ferry) S-train in the
greater Copenhagen area. International railway connections. Home of 
the Danish Queen, Margereth II, the parliament, and port to the Nordic
and Baltic countries.

NOTE:
Installing the revised TD font. To be able to see the Danish
characters I've had to 'doctor' the existing TD font. This is not a
problem with TD2 but rather a limitation of the programming language
used. Just copy the TD font directory together with the TD/8 file and
the td.font file into the fonts drawer of your TrainDriver directory.
It is probably wise to make a backup of the original files first
before overwriting them. If you do this and do not see the correct
characters on the screen it probably means that the font is already in
memory. In this case a soft reboot will solve the problem. If for any
reason you would like the original TD font back just overwrite the
'Danish' files with the original ones that came with your TD2 program.
